Supervised Classification of the Camp Fire 2018 with Random Forest¶

Classification based on Remote Sensing Imagery in Python 2.7¶

This python script shows the workflow of how to implement a supervised classification based on remote sensing data. It consists of certain preprocessing steps including a cloud mask, the classification based on random forest and postprocessing steps. The code is the result of an university assignment on which I worked together with Laura.

This project aims to analyze the extent of the burned area following the Camp Fire 2018 in Paradise. To execute this task, two Landsat 8 scenes were compared, a prefire and a postfire scene.

Note: This script for processing raster data is built on the classic modules gdal, numpy and matplotlib. Without doubt, there is room from improvement, e.g. using rasterio, especially for plotting. Also, being new to machine learning, it has to be noted that this is a very simple application in which some methodological approaches (e.g. the resampling strategy) probably can be questioned. As it is known from Random Forest models, also this application most likely is suffering from overfitting.

Modules and dependencies:

  • Python 2.7.17
  • gdal 3.0.2
  • os
  • glob2 0.7
  • numpy 1.15.1
  • re
  • matplotlib 2.2.4
  • scikit-learn 0.20.0
  • imbalanced-learn 0.4.2
  • scipy 1.2.3

Data download and preparation:

  • Download of the Landsat 8 scenes from the USGS Earth Explorer: 16.10. (Prefire) and 10.12.2018 (Postfire)
  • Cropping the extent of both scenes to the area of interest
  • Renaming the files following the pattern "LC08_Prefire_Paradise_B.tif" respectively "LC08_Postfire_Paradise_B.tif"
  • Collecting of training data in the Postfire scene
  • 8 classes: bare ground, masked cloud, water, shadow, vegetation, agriculture, sealed surfaces, burned area

Links and tutorials:

  • Scikit-learn (Random Forest Classifier)
  • Classification tutorial by Chris Holden
  • Quality Assessment Layer of Landsat 8

def read_raster (path):
    '''
    Reads tif-files as numpy array

    Parameter: absolute path to tif-file
    Returns: array, number of columns, number of rows, NoData value, geotransform, projection
    '''
    myrast = gdal.Open(path)
    NCOLS = myrast.RasterXSize
    NROWS = myrast.RasterYSize
    geotransform = myrast.GetGeoTransform()
    wkt_projection = myrast.GetProjection()
    mybandDSM = myrast.GetRasterBand(1)
    NoData = mybandDSM.GetNoDataValue()
    array_out = mybandDSM.ReadAsArray()

    return array_out, NCOLS, NROWS, NoData, geotransform, wkt_projection

def write_raster (array, geoTransform, projection, filename):
    '''
    Saves numpy array to tif-file 

    Parameter: array, geotransform, projection, filename (absolute path)
    '''
    NCOLS = array.shape[1]
    NROWS = array.shape[0]

    driver = gdal.GetDriverByName("GTiff")
    dataset = driver.Create(filename, NCOLS, NROWS, 1, gdal.GDT_Float64 )
    dataset.SetGeoTransform(geoTransform)
    dataset.SetProjection(projection)
    dataset.GetRasterBand(1).WriteArray(array)
    dataset.FlushCache()

    #return dataset, dataset.GetRasterBand(1)

def create_cloudmask (cloud_mask):
    '''
    Transforms the quality assessment layer of Landsat 8 to binary array (1 and NaN)
    This layer contains information on the quality / corruption of the single pixels of the respective scene
    Pixels impacted by atmospheric interferences, such as clouds, snow and ice, should be masked out (set to NaN)
    Only valid pixels should be used (set to 1 in cloudmask)

    Parameter: array 
    Returns: array (binary)
    '''
    cloud = [2800,2804,2808,2812,6896,6900,6904,6908]
    cloud_confidence_high = [2800,2804,2808,2812,6896,6900,6904,6908]
    cloud_shadow_high = [2976,2980,2984,2988,3008,3012,3016,3020,7072,7076,7080,7084,7104,7108,7112,7116]
    snow_ice_high = [3744,3748,3752,3756,3776,3780,3784,3788,7840,7844,7848,7852,7872,7876,7880,7884]

    #list with all values indicating pixels that should be masked 
    masked_values = cloud + cloud_confidence_high + snow_ice_high + cloud_shadow_high

    #binary cloudmask
    for i in masked_values:
        cloud_mask[cloud_mask == i]=0 
    cloud_mask[cloud_mask != 0]= 1 #valid pixels 
    cloud_mask[cloud_mask == 0]= np.nan #invalid pixels

    return cloud_mask

def apply_cloudmask (cloud_mask, raster):
    '''
    Application of the cloudmask to the raster files
    By multiplying the cloudmask with the raster arrays valid pixel remain unchanged (multiplied with 1) whereas invalix pixel will be set to NaN

    Parameter: binary cloudmask array, raster (array) to be masked
    '''
    raster [: ,:]*=cloud_mask

    return raster

def normalization (band1, band2): 
    '''
    calculation of NDVI and NBR indices
    
    Parameter: band1, band2
    Returns: calculated index as array 
    '''
    result = (band1-band2)/(band1+band2)

    return result

def sort_list (list):
    '''
    Sorts the list with paths to bands (.tif): prefire b1-b12,nbr,ndvi, postfire b1-b12, nbr,ndvi

    Parameter: list
    Returns: list (sorted)
    '''
    convert = lambda text: int(text) if text.isdigit() else text
    alphanum_key = lambda key: [ convert(c) for c in re.split("([0-9]+)", key) ]
    list_sorted = sorted(list, key = alphanum_key)

    #"postfire" alphabetically sorted before "prefire" 
    #"postfire" bands will be moved after "prefire" bands
    list_post = list_sorted[0:13] #temporarily saving postfire paths (first 13 items)
    del list_sorted[0:13] #deleting postfire paths
    list_sorted+=list_post #adding postfire paths againg

    return list_sorted

def redefine_nodata (array):
    '''
    NaN values will be set to -999999 
    Background: randomforest classifier cannot handle NaN values
    SimpleImputer can identify NaN values and assign (user defined) new values

    Parameter: array
    Returns: array
    '''
    imputer = SimpleImputer(missing_values=np.nan, strategy='constant', fill_value=-999999)
    imputer = imputer.fit(array)
    array_redefined = imputer.transform(array) 

    return array_redefined

def print_class_count(classes):
    '''
    Prints total number and number of pixel per class

    Parameter: array (pixel with assigned classes)
    '''
    n_samples = (classes > 0).sum()
    print "There are {n} training pixel".format(n=n_samples)

    labels = np.unique(classes[classes > 0])
    class_min, class_max = int(labels.min()), int(labels.max())

    print "Number of pixel per class:"
    for i in range (class_min, class_max+1):
        count = len(classes[classes==i])
        print "Class {k}: {c}".format(k=i, c=count)

def get_class_count_list(classes):
    '''
    Creates list with number of pixel per class

    Parameter: array (pixel with assigned classes)
    Return: List 
    '''
    list_counts = []
    labels = np.unique(classes[classes > 0])
    class_min, class_max = int(labels.min()), int(labels.max())
    for i in range (class_min, class_max+1):
        count = len(classes[classes==i])
        list_counts.append(count)

    return list_counts

def modal_filter(values):
    '''
    Function for calculating the modal filter in moving window
    Assigns the most frequent, surrounding pixel value to the central pixel
    The smoothing effect highlights trends of the pixel based classification; certain loss of information

    Parameter: array (pixel values in moving window)
    Returns: float (single pixel value = most frequent value in moving window)
    '''
    raster_mode = mode(values,axis=None,nan_policy ="omit") 

    return raster_mode[0]

def color_stretch(image, index, minmax=(0, 10000)):
    '''
    Preparation RGB polling of three bands
    Normalized bands (value range between 0 and 1) 
    
    Parameter: array (layerstack), index (bands as tupel), valuerange bands
    Returns: array (normalized bands)
    '''
    colors = image[:, :, index].astype(np.float64)

    max_val = minmax[1]
    min_val = minmax[0]

    # Enforce maximum and minimum values
    colors[colors[:, :, :] > max_val] = max_val
    colors[colors[:, :, :] < min_val] = min_val

    for b in range(colors.shape[2]):
        colors[:, :, b] = colors[:, :, b] * 1 / (max_val - min_val)

    return colors

Part I: Preprocessing¶

First, loading bands as numpy array.

In [5]:
#saving the absolute paths of the bands in list
band_list = glob.glob(os.path.join(path_data, "*.tif"))
#reading all bands as array with filename into dictionary
array_dict = {}
for i in band_list:
    filename = i.split("/")[-1][:-4]
    (array, NCOLS, NROWS, NoData, GeoTransform, projection) = read_raster(i)
    #Key: Filename --- Value: Numpy Array
    array_dict[filename] = array

To improve the data aggregation, the Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI) and Normalized Burn Ratio (NBR) are calculated for both scenes.

In [6]:
#requiring the arrays needed from dictionary
prefire_band4 = array_dict.get("LC08_Prefire_Paradise_B4") #RED
prefire_band5 = array_dict.get("LC08_Prefire_Paradise_B5") #NIR
prefire_band7 = array_dict.get("LC08_Prefire_Paradise_B7") #SWIR
postfire_band4 = array_dict.get("LC08_Postfire_Paradise_B4") #RED
postfire_band5 = array_dict.get("LC08_Postfire_Paradise_B5") #NIR
postfire_band7 = array_dict.get("LC08_Postfire_Paradise_B7") #SWIR

#calculation of the NDVI
ndvi_prefire = normalization (prefire_band5, prefire_band4)
ndvi_postfire = normalization (postfire_band5, postfire_band4)
#calculation of the NBR
nbr_prefire = normalization (prefire_band5, prefire_band7)
nbr_postfire = normalization (postfire_band5, postfire_band7)

#adding the indices to dictionary for accumulated data basis
array_dict["LC08_Prefire_Paradise_NDVI"] = ndvi_prefire
array_dict["LC08_Postfire_Paradise_NDVI"] = ndvi_postfire
array_dict["LC08_Prefire_Paradise_NBR"] = nbr_prefire
array_dict["LC08_Postfire_Paradise_NBR"] = nbr_postfire

Applying the cloud mask¶

To a certain degree, the postfire scene is impacted by atmospheric intereferences. To not falsify the classification, the respective pixels in both the prefire and postfire scene will be set to NaN. To achieve this, the information provided by the quality assessment layer for the postfire scene ist used. Pixel impacted by cloud, cloud shadow, snow and ice will be masked (see Function Definition). Find more information on the QA layer here.

In [7]:
#loading the quality assessment layer of the postfire scene
(postfire_QA, NCOLS, NROWS, NoData, GeoTransform, Projection) = read_raster(path_postfire_QA)
#creating the binary cloud mask
cloud_mask = create_cloudmask(postfire_QA)

#applying the cloud mask to all bands
masked_array_dict = {}
for key in array_dict:
    raster_to_be_masked = array_dict.get(key)
    raster_masked = apply_cloudmask(cloud_mask, raster_to_be_masked)
    
    #masked arrays with corresponding naming
    if "Prefire" in key:
        keyname = "LC08_Prefire_Paradise_masked" + key[21:] #+Band
    elif "Postfire" in key:
        keyname = "LC08_Postfire_Paradise_masked" + key[22:] #+Band

    #key: array - value: bandname
    masked_array_dict[keyname] = raster_masked

Part II: Classification¶

This section starts by again loading the masked bands from output_tmp (Background: Originally, this script was split in two scripts). One could adapt the script by directly transfering the arrays (keys) of the "masked_array_dict" into a list which is required for the further step of creating a layerstack. However, by doing this, the desired order (numerical (B1 - B11) and temporal (first prefire then postfire scene)) of the arrays / bands could not be ensured. This is room for improvement.

Resampling of training dataset¶

Balancing the number of pixels per class by under- or oversampling them to the median of all classes.
Note: this approach (first undersampling, then synthetically oversampling) could be questioned and should rather be tested step by step (quality assessment). However, for this case, it was carried out to exemplify how to balance the classes to ensure that also classes with a smaller number of pixels can be properly predicted.

Balancing the unequal distribution within the training dataset. Median as sampling strategy.

In [19]:
list_counts = get_class_count_list(df_train[:,26][df_train[:,26] > 0]) #get_class_clount_list creats list with number of pixel per class
array_counts = np.asarray(list_counts) 
counts_median = int(np.median(array_counts))

#undersampling
rus = RandomUnderSampler(random_state=3, sampling_strategy={4:counts_median, 5:counts_median, 6:counts_median, 8:counts_median})
#sampling_strategy --> classes greater than median (selected manually)
X_rus, y_rus = rus.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

#oversampling with SMOTE
smote = SMOTE(random_state=3, sampling_strategy={1:counts_median, 2:counts_median, 3:counts_median, 7:counts_median})
X_resampled, y_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X_rus, y_rus)
#print information of number and distribution of pixels
print_class_count(y_resampled)

As we can see, the indices (NDVI and NBR) - explicitely compiled for a better data basis - explain a great share of the classification. Also, Band 5 (NIR) has a high explanatory importance which does not surprise, as its values indicate the reflectance of vegetation, which - in different state - dominates the satellite scene.

Part III: Postprocessing¶

Reduction of the Salt-and-Pepper-Effect¶

The Salt-and-Pepper-Effect results from the pixel based classification, which can be reduced by applying a filter, such as a modal filter in a 3x3 moving window. This filter assigns the most frequent, surrounding pixel value to the central pixel. The respective function had to be defined (see "Function Definitions"). The smoothing effect of the filter highlights trends of the pixel based classification, which is why the certain loss of information can be accepted.

In [25]:
class_prediction_filtered = generic_filter(class_prediction,function=modal_filter,size=3)

Visualization with matplotlib¶

For labeling and assigning colors to the classes a dictionary is set up and then translated into the necessary lists. This allows to change labels and color assignments more quickly.

In [26]:
classes = {
    1 : ("Bare Area", "#964b00"),
    2 : ("Masked Cloud","#ffffff"),
    3 : ("Water", "#1f78b4"),
    4 : ("Shadow (Terrain)", "#000000"),
    5 : ("Vegetation", "#33a02c"),
    6 : ("Agricultural Area", "#b2df8a"),
    7 : ("Sealed Area", "#edb60e"),
    8 : ("Burned Area","#e44dcc")}

classes_colors = []
classes_labels = []

for key in classes:
    values = classes.get(key)
    label = values[0]
    color = values[1]

    classes_labels.append(label)
    classes_colors.append(color)

n_classes = class_prediction.max()
